  "response_text": "Here is a comprehensive grocery list for a family of four for one week. This list is designed to be balanced, versatile, and budget-friendly, covering breakfast, lunch, dinner, and snacks. It assumes you have basic pantry staples (salt, pepper, oil, vinegar, spices) and uses common ingredients that can be mixed and matched to avoid waste.\n\n### Key Principles\n- **Plan for leftovers:** Many dinners yield enough for lunch the next day.\n- **Buy in bulk:** Rice, oats, and frozen vegetables are cost-effective.\n- **Seasonal produce:** Adjust fresh fruits and vegetables based on what’s in season and on sale.\n\n---\n\n## 🛒 The Grocery List\n\n### 🥩 Protein (Meat, Fish, & Plant-Based)\n- **Chicken:** 2 lbs boneless, skinless chicken breasts or thighs (for stir-fry, salads, or tacos)\n- **Ground beef or turkey:** 1 lb (for pasta sauce, tacos, or burgers)\n- **Fish or tofu:** 1 lb salmon fillets or firm tofu (for one dinner)\n- **Eggs:** 1 dozen (breakfast, baking, or quick dinners)\n- **Beans/lentils:** 2 cans (black beans, chickpeas, or lentils) – for tacos, soups, or salads\n\n### 🥦 Fresh Vegetables\n- **Onions:** 3 medium (base for many meals)\n- **Garlic:** 1 head\n- **Bell peppers:** 2 (any color)\n- **Carrots:** 1 bag (for snacks, salads, or roasting)\n- **Broccoli or cauliflower:** 1 head (roast or steam)\n- **Spinach or kale:** 1 bag (for salads, smoothies, or wilting into pasta)\n- **Zucchini or summer squash:** 2 (for stir-fry or pasta)\n- **Tomatoes:** 4 medium (slicing or cooking)\n- **Lettuce:** 1 head (romaine or iceberg)\n- **Avocados:** 2 (for toast, salads, or tacos)\n- **Potatoes or sweet potatoes:** 4-5 medium (baked, roasted, or mashed)\n- **Lemons:** 2 (for dressing, fish, or tea)\n\n### 🍎 Fresh Fruit\n- **Bananas:** 6 (breakfast, snacks, smoothies)\n- **Apples or oranges:** 6-8 (lunch snacks)\n- **Berries or grapes:** 1 pint (treat for snacks or breakfast)\n- **Seasonal fruit:** e.g., melon, mango, or pears – 1-2 pieces\n\n### 🧀 Dairy & Alternatives\n- **Milk or plant-based milk:** 1 gallon (drinking, cereal, cooking)\n- **Yogurt:** 1 large tub (plain or vanilla, for breakfast or snacks)\n- **Cheese:** 1 block cheddar or mozzarella (shred for tacos, pasta, or sandwiches)\n- **Butter or margarine:** 1 stick (cooking, toast)\n- **Cottage cheese or ricotta:** optional (for lasagna or toast)\n\n### 🍞 Grains & Bread\n- **Whole wheat bread:** 1 loaf (sandwiches, toast)\n- **Tortillas (corn or flour):** 1 pack (tacos, wraps, quesadillas)\n- **Rice (brown or white):** 1 bag (2 cups dry)\n- **Pasta:** 1 box (spaghetti, penne, or rotini)\n- **Oats:** 1 container (for oatmeal or baked goods)\n- **Crackers or rice cakes:** 1 box (for snacks)\n\n### 🥫 Pantry Staples (if not already on hand)\n- **Olive oil & vegetable oil**\n- **Salt, black pepper, garlic powder, chili powder, cumin, Italian seasoning**\n- **Soy sauce or tamari** (for stir-fry)\n- **Vinegar** (apple cider or balsamic)\n- **Canned tomatoes** (1 can crushed or diced)\n- **Tomato sauce** (1 small can)\n- **Peanut butter or almond butter** (1 jar)\n- **Honey or maple syrup**\n- **Chicken or vegetable broth** (1 box or cubes)\n- **Flour** (for thickening or baking)\n\n### 🥜 Snacks & Misc\n- **Nuts or trail mix:** 1 bag\n- **Dried fruit:** raisins, apricots, or dates\n- **Popcorn kernels or microwave popcorn:** 1 bag\n- **Dark chocolate chips or bar:** for occasional treat\n\n### 🧊 Frozen Section\n- **Frozen vegetables:** 1 bag mixed (peas, corn, green beans) – easy side dish\n- **Frozen fruit:** 1 bag (berries or mango for smoothies)\n- **Frozen pizza or veggie burgers:** 1 (for a busy night)\n- **Ice cream or frozen yogurt:** 1 container (treat)\n\n---\n\n## 📅 Sample Weekly Meal Plan (to match the list)\n\n| Day | Breakfast | Lunch | Dinner |\n|-----|-----------|-------|--------|\n| Mon | Oatmeal with berries | Leftover pasta | Chicken stir-fry with broccoli & rice |\n| Tue | Scrambled eggs + toast | Turkey/bean tacos | Salmon (or tofu) with roasted potatoes & spinach |\n| Wed | Yogurt + banana | Leftover salmon/tacos | Pasta with ground meat sauce + side salad |\n| Thu | Smoothie (frozen fruit, spinach, yogurt) | Leftover pasta | Black bean & veggie quesadillas |\n| Fri | Avocado toast + egg | Tuna/egg salad sandwich | Homemade pizza (use tortillas or bread) + side veggies |\n| Sat | Pancakes (from flour, eggs, milk) | Leftover pizza | Baked chicken with roasted carrots & potatoes |\n| Sun | Cereal + milk | Leftover chicken + salad | Soup (lentil or veggie) with bread |\n\n---\n\n## 💡 Tips to Save Money & Reduce Waste\n- **Use leftovers creatively:** Turn roasted veggies into a frittata or soup.\n- **Buy store brands** for pantry items like rice, canned goods, and frozen veggies.\n- **Check your fridge/pantry** before shopping – you may already have spices, oil, or condiments.\n- **Cook once, eat twice:** Double a dinner recipe (like chili or pasta sauce) to freeze for another week.\n\nThis list should cost between **$100–$180** depending on your location, store, and whether you buy organic. Adjust quantities based on your family’s appetite and dietary restrictions. Enjoy your week of meals!",
